04202nam a22006615i 9780776629315DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807766293157 a10.1515/97807766293152doi  a(DE-B1597)668115  a(OCoLC)1144170549  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBF697b.R63 2020 7aPSY0280002bisacsh04a155.22231 aRobertson, Lloyd Hawkeye, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Evolved Self :bMapping an Understanding of Who We Are /cLloyd Hawkeye Robertson. 1aOttawa : bUniversity of Ottawa Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (302 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHealth and Society00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Figures -- tList of Tables -- t1. Necessity and Invention in Counselling -- t2. The Self Within Euro-American Thought -- t3. The Self in Collectivist Cultures -- t4. The Potential of the Meme -- t5. Mapping the Self from Personal Narratives -- t6. Memes, Themes, and Humanness -- t7. Implications of Self-Mapping for Psychological Practice -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this work the self, which is core to such concepts as self-esteem and self-actualization, is mapped using elemental units of culture called memes. To understand this self, we draw on Western philosophy, major schools of psychology, and the cross-cultural experience of the self in both collectivist and individualist cultures.  With this grounding a diverse sample of eleven selves representing three genders are mapped and analyzed, grouped in the following clusters: 1) North American selves built through participation in sports; 2) selves centred on notions of North American aboriginality; 3) selves of individuals following a secular humanist paradigm; and 4) selves from China and Russia. Two methods of self-mapping are described. The results support a hypothesis that a healthy or functional self is composed of fundamental elements including constancy, volition, uniqueness, productivity, intimacy, and social interest. The application of this research and the method of self-mapping to counselling and psychotherapy are explored. A disciplinary paradigm is proposed uniting major schools of psychotherapy.  This work will be of interest to philosophers, psychologists, social workers, sociologists, and all who have wondered how they come to define themselves in the ways that they do.  Published in English.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCounseling. 0aCulture. 0aEgo (Psychology). 0aFree will and determinism. 0aMemes. 0aPsychotherapy. 0aSelf. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Psychotherapy / General.2bisacsh  aIdentity.  aMemes.  aSelf-mapping.  aSelf-structure.  aSelf.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311127253508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020z978311127473740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780776629315?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780776629315423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780776629315/original  a978-3-11-127253-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-127473-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles